This paper discusses the limitations of machine learning models when applied to social systems, which falls under the category of "social impact" in computer science. The paper also focuses on the conceptual, procedural, and statistical limitations of these models, which are relevant to the sub-categories of "machine learning" (cs.LG) and "artificial intelligence" (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper discusses the potential consequences of these limitations, which could be relevant to the sub-categories of "cybersecurity" (cs.CR) and "social and information networks" (cs.SI).
